== Pythagorean Triples
 The Pythagorean triples are uniquely generated by
 #mitex(`a=k\cdot (m^{2}-n^{2}),\ \,b=k\cdot (2mn),\ \,c=k\cdot (m^{2}+n^{2}),`)
 with #mi(`m > n > 0`), #mi(`k > 0`), #mi(`m \bot n`), and either #mi(`m`) or #mi(`n`) even.

== Primes
	#mi(`p=962592769`) is such that #mi(`2^{21} \mid p-1`), which may be useful. For hashing
	use 970592641 (31-bit number), 31443539979727 (45-bit), 3006703054056749
	(52-bit). There are 78498 primes less than 1 000 000.

	Primitive roots exist modulo any prime power #mi(`p^a`), except for #mi(`p = 2, a > 2`), and there are #mi(`\phi(\phi(p^a))`) many.
	For #mi(`p = 2, a > 2`), the group #mi(`\mathbb Z_{2^a}^\times`) is instead isomorphic to #mi(`\mathbb Z_2 \times \mathbb Z_{2^{a-2}}`).

== Estimates
	#mi(`\sum_{d|n} d = O(n \log \log n)`).

	The number of divisors of #mi(`n`) is at most around 100 for #mi(`n < 5e4`), 500 for #mi(`n < 1e7`), 2000 for #mi(`n < 1e10`), 200\,000 for #mi(`n < 1e19`).

